JOHN:
Yeah, it really is horrible.

00:04:10,584 --> 00:04:11,618
I'm out.

00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:16,923
Okay, so this is the shortest
pitch in "Shark Tank" history.

00:04:16,923 --> 00:04:18,725
I'm gonna let you
have a chance to explain

00:04:18,725 --> 00:04:20,994
why you're worth
$10 million.

00:04:20,994 --> 00:04:24,898
Well, this year, we're on track
to do $1.5 million in sales.

00:04:24,898 --> 00:04:28,835
We've sold over 276,000 units
over the past two years.

00:04:28,835 --> 00:04:32,739
We should be in 1,000 new stores
in the coming six months.

00:04:32,739 --> 00:04:34,741
We've done
hundreds of demos.

00:04:34,741 --> 00:04:36,543
I would say
that 9 out of the 10 people

00:04:36,543 --> 00:04:38,578
that try it in the store
like it.

00:04:38,578 --> 00:04:39,846
What do you think
about that?

00:04:39,846 --> 00:04:41,148
Hey, look,
just 'cause I don't like it

00:04:41,148 --> 00:04:42,682
doesn't mean there
aren't people who do like it.

00:04:44,017 --> 00:04:45,418
O'LEARY: Which one
of my assumptions is wrong?

00:04:45,418 --> 00:04:46,653
This is a commodity.

00:04:46,653 --> 00:04:48,889
Anybody can package this
and sell it.

00:04:48,889 --> 00:04:50,390
No one's ever heard of it,

00:04:50,390 --> 00:04:52,692
so you've got a marketing job
from hell.

00:04:52,692 --> 00:04:56,329
Why are you asking
for $1 million for 10%?

00:04:56,329 --> 00:04:59,399
How -- how -- under what
scenario on what planet

00:04:59,399 --> 00:05:00,801
would that make sense
to an investor?

00:05:03,236 --> 00:05:06,406
This is actually a
product that we've had
a lot of interest from

00:05:06,406 --> 00:05:08,074
from some
very large companies.

00:05:08,074 --> 00:05:11,344
I've actually found references
over 150 years old

00:05:11,344 --> 00:05:13,079
from people
who have tried to do this.

00:05:13,079 --> 00:05:15,682
And they've not been able
to do that for a few reasons.

00:05:15,682 --> 00:05:18,285
The roasting is something
that's completely different

00:05:18,285 --> 00:05:20,086
from what's done
with normal chocolate products

00:05:20,086 --> 00:05:21,254
as well
as coffee products.

00:05:21,254 --> 00:05:22,622
Oh, so you're telling me
the process

00:05:22,622 --> 00:05:24,724
by which you make your crio bean
is proprietary and unique?

00:05:24,724 --> 00:05:25,959
Absolutely.

00:05:25,959 --> 00:05:27,527
And that is something
we have patent pending.

00:05:29,496 --> 00:05:32,432
Who are you selling it to?
Through what medium?

00:05:32,432 --> 00:05:34,901
FOTHERINGHAM: 60% of our sales
are in grocery stores.

00:05:34,901 --> 00:05:36,469
We're in 500 stores
currently --

00:05:36,469 --> 00:05:39,139
on slate to be in 1,500 stores
by the end of the year.

00:05:39,139 --> 00:05:41,074
Do you have reorders
in this short period of time?

00:05:41,074 --> 00:05:42,142
Absolutely.

00:05:42,142 --> 00:05:43,743
And I know your experience
is different,

00:05:43,743 --> 00:05:44,978
but to be honest
with you,

00:05:44,978 --> 00:05:46,646
a lot of times,
people try it their first try,

00:05:46,646 --> 00:05:47,848
and you don't know
what to expect.

00:05:47,848 --> 00:05:49,416
You're either thinking
hot chocolate

00:05:49,416 --> 00:05:50,951
or you're thinking
coffee.

00:05:50,951 --> 00:05:52,185
This is neither one
of those.

00:05:52,185 --> 00:05:53,753
O'LEARY:
Why is that a good thing?

00:05:53,753 --> 00:05:55,655
You have to educate
an entire generation

00:05:55,655 --> 00:05:57,090
that they should be
drinking this,

00:05:57,090 --> 00:05:59,359
supposedly, because it's better
for them than coffee

00:05:59,359 --> 00:06:01,494
and that the taste is,
at least, equivalent.

00:06:01,494 --> 00:06:04,297
I mean, I can see people --
I think we have
five opinions here,

00:06:04,297 --> 00:06:05,632
and everybody thought
the taste --

00:06:05,632 --> 00:06:07,267
no, not me. I thought
the taste was fine.

00:06:07,267 --> 00:06:09,569
What you were expecting
was something that tasted
like coffee.

00:06:09,569 --> 00:06:11,204
No, that's not what
I was expecting at all.

00:06:11,204 --> 00:06:13,006
I was looking for
a coffee replacement,

00:06:13,006 --> 00:06:14,774
not knowing
what to expect.

00:06:14,774 --> 00:06:18,445
It just tastes like cocoa beans
mashed up, ripe,

00:06:18,445 --> 00:06:21,781
and hot water put
in, and there wasn't
enough cocoa put in.

00:06:21,781 --> 00:06:22,983
Well, Mark, they're --
they're selling $1.5 million.

00:06:22,983 --> 00:06:25,151
Some people like it.
So, here's the thing --

00:06:25,151 --> 00:06:27,921
how much you making
on the $1.5 million?

00:06:27,921 --> 00:06:30,257
This year,
we should do $150,000.

00:06:30,257 --> 00:06:32,559
So let's just
think about this.
That's awesome.
That's all that matters, right?

00:06:32,559 --> 00:06:35,896
You're asking me to pay
100 times your profit.

00:06:35,896 --> 00:06:38,798
Well, and so,
part of that is --

00:06:38,798 --> 00:06:41,234
I mean,
I have to punish you now.

00:06:41,234 --> 00:06:44,237
Why in the world
would you value yourself

00:06:44,237 --> 00:06:47,240
at such a number
that it is impossible --

00:06:47,240 --> 00:06:49,743
that's what they've been trying
to figure out for 150 years.

00:06:49,743 --> 00:06:52,913
[ laughter ]
Nobody would ever pay you
that valuation.

00:06:52,913 --> 00:06:55,548
You're not worth
100 times your profit.

00:06:55,548 --> 00:06:57,884
I think you're screwed.
I'm out.

00:07:00,520 --> 00:07:02,756
And then there
was Barbara.

00:07:04,991 --> 00:07:06,159
Barbara,
what are you gonna do?

00:07:06,159 --> 00:07:08,094
I think you're screwed.
I'm out.

00:07:08,094 --> 00:07:10,196
[ laughter ]
Oh, Barbara!

00:07:10,196 --> 00:07:12,432
